{"id":"2003.01435","submitter":"Gerhard Roehrle","authors":"Paul M\\\"ucksch and Gerhard Roehrle","title":"Accurate Arrangements","comments":"29 pages; 1 Figure; v2 small changes; v3 final version: added Example\n  3.13 and Example 4.5 to exemplify Theorem 3.11 and Theorem 4.3. Added in new\n  reference [ATT20] in Remark 5.6. To appear in Advances in Math","journal-ref":"Adv. Math. 383, Article ID 107702, 30 p. (2021)","doi":"10.1016/j.aim.2021.107702","report-no":null,"categories":"math.GR math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $\\mathscr A$ be a Coxeter arrangement of rank $\\ell$. In 1987 Orlik,\nSolomon and Terao conjectured that for every $1\\leq d \\leq \\ell$, the first $d$\nexponents of $\\mathscr A$ -- when listed in increasing order -- are realized as\nthe exponents of a free restriction of $\\mathscr A$ to some intersection of\nreflecting hyperplanes of $\\mathscr A$ of dimension $d$. This conjecture does\nfollow from rather extensive case-by-case studies by Orlik and Terao from 1992\nand 1993, where they show that all restrictions of Coxeter arrangements are\nfree. We call a general free arrangements with this natural property involving\ntheir free restrictions accurate. In this paper we initialize their systematic\nstudy. Our principal result shows that MAT-free arrangements, a notion recently\nintroduced by Cuntz and M\\\"ucksch, are accurate. This theorem in turn directly\nimplies this special property for all ideal subarrangements of Weyl\narrangements. In particular, this gives a new, simpler and uniform proof of the\naforementioned conjecture of Orlik, Solomon and Terao for Weyl arrangements\nwhich is free of any case-by-case considerations. Another application of a\nslightly more general formulation of our main theorem shows that extended Shi\narrangements, extended Catalan arrangements and ideal-Shi arrangements share\nthis property as well. We also study arrangements that satisfy a slightly\nweaker condition, called almost accurate arrangements, where we simply\ndisregard the ordering of the exponents involved. This property in turn is\nimplied by many well established concepts of freeness such as supersolvability\nand divisional freeness.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 3 Mar 2020 10:40:50 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 9 Mar 2020 12:22:22 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 8 Mar 2021 09:46:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-21"}
